To solve this level I used to many ways such as:
sort data.txt | uniq -c | less
which will sort the repeated lines and it will count them, and you can find the only repeated once sorted and counted.

And this method which is the best one:
sort data.txt | uniq -c | sort -n | head -n 1
sort data.txt — sorts all lines alphabetically (required because uniq only catches duplicates that are adjacent)
uniq -c — collapses consecutive duplicate lines and prefixes each with a count of how many times it occurred
sort -n — sorts those counts numerically, smallest first
head -n 1 — grabs the very first result, i.e. the line with the lowest count (which will be 1 — the line that occurs only once)


